d1281639-d3cc-4b6c-a7f7-9300a51c79c4.3c4de3fc-dd5d-4780-aebf-6b3e3d8b08e9.description=
This operation runs a SQL SELECT query.
The first row is returned on the first run of the operation.
Subsequent calls with the same information will return the other rows.

Inputs\:
    DBServerName - The hostname or ip address of the database server.
    DbType - The type of database to connect to. 
Valid values\: Oracle, MSSQL, Sybase, Netcool, DB2 and Custom.
Default value\: Oracle
    Username - The username to use when connecting to the server.
    Password - The password to use when connecting to the server.
    instance - The name instance of MSSQL Server. Leave it blank for default instance.
Example\: MSSQLSERVER
    DbPort - The port to connect to.
Valid values\: Oracle\: 1521, MSSQL\: 1433, Sybase\: 5000, Netcool\: 4100, DB2\: 50000.
    Database - The name of the database to connect to.
    authenticationType - The type of authentication used to access the database (applicable only to MSSQL type). 
Valid values\: sql, windows (for MSSQL)
default value\: sql
    dbClass - The class name of the JDBC driver to use.
    dbURL - The URL required to load up the driver and make your connection.
    Command - The SQL query to execute.
    Delimiter - The delimiter to use between resulted values in "returnResult" and column names in "columnNames".
    Key - The key to help keep multiple query results distinct.
    timeout - Seconds to wait before timing out the SQL command execution. When the default value is used, there is no limit on the amount of time allowed for a running command to complete.
Default values\: 0 
    databasePoolingProperties - Properties for database pooling configuration. This parameter replaces the databasePooling.properties file from 9x version (you may copy-paste the file content here). Pooling is disabled by default. For more details check the /Library/Operations/Database/JDBC folder description.
Example\: db.pooling.enable\=true
    resultSetType - the result set type. See JDBC folder description for more details.
Valid values\: TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY, TYPE_SCROLL_INSENSITIVE,TYPE_SCROLL_SENSITIVE.
Default value\: TYPE_SCROLL_INSENSITIVE except DB2 which is overridden to TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY
    resultSetConcurrency - the result set concurrency. See JDBC folder description for more details.
Valid values\: CONCUR_READ_ONLY, CONCUR_UPDATABLE
Default value\: CONCUR_READ_ONLY
    ignoreCase - If set to true the inputs' letters case will be ignored and converted to lowercase.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: true

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the data of one row, separated by the "Delimiter". 
    columnNames - The names of all the columns returned, separated by the "Delimiter".
    rowsLeft - The number of remaining rows that match the query.

Responses\:
    more items - More rows are available for retrieval.
    no more items - No more rows are available.
    failure - Failed to execute the command.

Notes\: 
1. SQL statement other than SELECT statement (like INSERT, UPDATE or DELETE) is not supported. In case statements other than SELECT are executed then the operation will fail but the statements might get partially or fully executed in the database.
2. If the column type is "ntext", the "returnResult" returns the name of the JDBC driver instead of the actual column value. In this case, use the "SQL Query LOB" operation instead.

Note\:
    Check the JDBC folder description for details on how to load database connectors.

d1281639-d3cc-4b6c-a7f7-9300a51c79c4.9b6ea221-05b7-4906-889a-d8e0afdc7c64.description=
This operation iterates through a list of values. It is not recommended to modify the value of the "list" and "separator" inputs during the iteration process.

Inputs\:
    list - The list to iterate through.
    separator - A delimiter separating the list elements.
Default value\: ‘,’ (comma) 

Results\:
    resultString - The current list element (if the response is "has more").

Responses\:
    has more - Another value was found in the list and it has been returned.
    no more - The iterator has gone through the entire list. This response is returned once per list iteration.  A subsequent call to the List iterator operation restarts the list iteration process.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
   The position of the iterator in the list is tracked by each step's unique identifier. Therefore, you can simultaneously iterate through the same list from multiple steps.
d1281639-d3cc-4b6c-a7f7-9300a51c79c4.9c453e06-4911-4f10-a4e6-f1772c8f3929.description=
This workflow returns the user identifier id for the given user.

Inputs-
csaUser–  CSA User name
Default value\: Gets from CSA_OO_USER system property which is set to "ooInboundUser"
authType - The authentication type that this operation uses when trying to execute the request on the target server.
Valid values\: basic, form, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication).
Default value\: anonymous - authentication not used when executing the request.
kerberosConfFile - The path to the Kerberos configuration file. If this input is empty the kdc (Key Distribution Center) and realm will get their values from the full domain name which is obtained from the url of the web server.
timeout - The number of milliseconds to wait for a connection to be established. This input should be assigned a value greater than or equal to zero. A timeout value of zero is an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0.
socketTimeout - The number of milliseconds to wait for the data to be retrieved. This input should be assigned a value greater than or equal to zero. A socketTimeout value of zero is an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0.
useCookies - If true, enables cookie tracking. Cookies will be stored between consecutive calls. This is a boolean input. If a non-boolean value is specified, it will take the default value.
Default value\: true.
followRedirects - If true, the GET command automatically follows redirects. This is a boolean input. If a non-boolean value is specified, it will take the default value.
Default value\: true
proxy - A proxy to use when accessing the web site.
proxyPort - The port on the proxy to connect to.
proxyUsername - The username to use when connecting to the proxy.
proxyPassword - The password to use when connecting to the proxy.
encodeURL - If true, automatically encodes the URL. This is a boolean input. If a non-boolean value is specified, it will take the default value.
Default value\: false.
userAgent - The value that should be used if the HTTP header USER_AGENT has to be overridden.
trustAllRoots - If true, enables weak security over SSL. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it.
Default value\: true
keystore - URL of the keystore file or local path to it (e.g. %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts). It may be empty if HTTPS client authentication is not to be used.
keystorePassword - Password to unlock the keystore.
trustKeystore - URL of the truststore file or local path to it (e.g. %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts). It may be empty if HTTPS server authentication is not to be used.
trustPassword - Password to unlock the truststore.

Outputs-
userIdentifier – User identifier id for the given user
